               Either a man may be without Sinne,An other obiection. or he can not be without Sinne. If he can not, what reason is it, that Sinne that can not be but present, should be imputed? If he may be without Sinne, how is will then bounde by Necessitie, which might haue eschued the thyng that was committed?
               And to this also Augustine maketh Aunswere: That a man may in deede be without Sinne if God do helpe him, we do not deny: but this reason proueth not, that there is any man without Sinne, that is not holpen, neither do we agree thereunto. But when a man may be without sinne, and by whom, that is the thyng that is in question. If thou wilt say in this present life, and in the body of this death, how then do we pray in this life, forgeue vs our sinnes? If mā can of him selfe be without Sinne. Ergo, Christ dyed in vayne. &amp;c. But Osorius vnderproppeth his Freewill here, with this crooch in couplyng the grace of God with it, disputyng on this wise.
               
