                  Osorius pag. 171. but it doth worke thys rather, both to make men more willyng to embrace vertue, and yet desiste not neuerthelesse to stand in the meane tyme alwayes in

feare of the seueritie of Gods Iudgement. And why so I pray you? For whosoeuer are caried with ardent fayth vnto Christ,How the Fayth of the Catholickes is ioyned with hope and feare. those doth he beautifie with most aboūdant stoare of vertue: Moreouer whenas the same men do know, that the same Christ will be a seuere Iudge against them, which will not do hys commaundementes, they are alwayes in continuall feare. Well: and whereunto tendeth all this (Osorius) so maisterly debated touching Fayth, Hope and Feare? for I cō
