the Popes aucthoritie. By what Argument do you proue this to be true? Forsooth bycause Osorius hath spoken the word. But farre otherwise spake, and did Augustine, Ierome, and Chrisostome, of whom we made mention before. Otherwise also spake Gelasius a Bishop of Rome, who doth franckly and boldly professe, that the priuiledges of the Church are in the power of the Emperour, deliuered vnto him from aboue. I speake not here of the person, man or woman, nor yet of ye maners of Princes: but of ye authoritie: which whether happē to mā or womā, if their prerogatiue be warranted by ye ordinaunce of God: there is no cause why it should be defaced for ye peéuish pratyng of one Portingall.
